Perfect! You have:

âœ… A bastion host (public EC2) with manually created key pair (private + public key)

â—ï¸ But you don't have the original key for the private EC2 instance

âœ… You want to use the bastion host to access the private EC2 instance

âœ… Solution: Use your own public key (from bastion) to access the private instance
We will do this without restarting or detaching the private instance.

ğŸ› ï¸ Full Step-by-Step Plan (No Keypair, No NAT)
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Copy your public key into the private EC2 instance
You already generated a key pair on the bastion host:
# On Bastion Host
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
Example:
ssh-rsa AAAAB3Nza...your_key_here... user@host



ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Add this public key to the private EC2â€™s ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
But... you donâ€™t have SSH or SSM access yet to the private instance, so youâ€™ll need to:

âœ… Option 1 (Best): Use SSM Session Manager (if already enabled)
If SSM is working (we configured endpoints), check:

Go to AWS Console â†’ EC2 â†’ Instances
Select your private instance
Click Connect â†’ Session Manager tab
Click Connect
Then:mkdir -p ~/.ssh
echo "ssh-rsa AAAAB3Nza... your key ..." >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
Done âœ… â€” now from Bastion Host:
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa ec2-user@<PRIVATE-IP>

ğŸ” chmod 400 â€” for Private Key (on Bastion)
âœ… Purpose:
Tells SSH: â€œOnly the file owner (you) can read this private key.â€
ğŸ”¹ Use on Bastion host:
chmod 400 ~/.ssh/mykey


ğŸ”‘ chmod 600 â€” for authorized_keys (on Private EC2 via SSM)
âœ… Purpose:
Means: â€œOnly the owner (e.g., ubuntu) can read/write this file.â€

ğŸ”¹ Use inside private instance:
chmod 600 /home/ubuntu/.ssh/authorized_keys




âœ… Step-by-Step to Inject SSH Key for ubuntu User
ğŸ”¹ 1. Stay in SSM shell (you are in /home/ssm-user)
Now switch to root:
sudo -i
âœ… To switch to the ubuntu user:
sudo su - ubuntu

ğŸ”¹ 2. Create .ssh directory for ubuntu user
mkdir -p /home/ubuntu/.ssh
nano /home/ubuntu/.ssh/authorized_keys
ğŸ“‹ Paste your public key from Bastion here (the one from ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub)

